    <a title="Frog" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45833437-frog"><img alt="Frog" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509854415p2/45833437.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1360711368?book_show_action=true">Aug 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frog" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frog" href="/user/show/45833437-frog">Frog</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781416905271" href="/book/show/11311.The_Boggart">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/45833437-frog?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1360711368" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16682532911572649271">Similar to Spiderwick, this rare creature is rewarding to read about, while the social arcs of contemporary characters are tacked on in grasp at an unnecessary formula.<br/><br/>From a technical perspective, Susan Cooper is obviously a good writer with few unnecessary words. However, certain ideas have an inharmonious feel from the main tone about Scotland and the Boggart with a lingering feeling of ulterior motive.<br/><br/>Some family dynamics, the thread about a teen drug dealer with a heart of gold, the gang of</span>
  <span id="freeText16682532911572649271" style="display:none">Similar to Spiderwick, this rare creature is rewarding to read about, while the social arcs of contemporary characters are tacked on in grasp at an unnecessary formula.<br /><br />From a technical perspective, Susan Cooper is obviously a good writer with few unnecessary words. However, certain ideas have an inharmonious feel from the main tone about Scotland and the Boggart with a lingering feeling of ulterior motive.<br /><br />Some family dynamics, the thread about a teen drug dealer with a heart of gold, the gang of (painfully dated) computer nerds, and some of the adult characters from the theater and antique shop are irrelevant and jarring, as if from a saccharine 90s movie. <br /><br />I would rather delete or ignore these threads and read only the Boggart's perspective, which itself is shockingly well done. That said, I might have preferred if he stayed in Scotland rather than going across the sea to a muggle city, although I did enjoy when he became a hockey puck.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16682532911572649271" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


